author: @jasonlanders1397
text:
(Calling-out of "Capy-Cots", who didn't understand a Joker learning to become a humble man; but preferred to launch laughter--into the highlights of madness.)

BED

In the shadows where wisdom dances, unseen,

A playful jest blooms, wrapped in serene,
"Capy-Cots," they whispered, but missed the flame,

A genius beckoned, unbound by name.

The Jokerâ€™s mask, once painted in jest,
Sought not the crowdâ€™s roar but a quiet rest.

To shed the guise, to learn, to standâ€”
A humble heart, not a trembling hand.

Yet the world, enamored by chaos and glee,
Laughed not with him, but at what they see.

Highlights of madness, a dazzling show,
Obscured the seed he yearned to sow.

Oh, the mark they missed, the deeper thread,
A soul reborn where wild paths led.

For beneath the mask and the jesting art,
Lies a fragile, striving, human heart.

-phoenix cowboy

text:
The opening of this trailer says it all. The moment the reporter says, â€œHeâ€™s a monster,â€ it just hits. Reflecting on the world today and reading the hate this movie and Arthur receive in the comments (and within the movie itself) touches something deeper. Arthur needed help, but society failed him. Instead, they used him as a vehicle to channel their own fear, not realizing how this destroys the most helpless, Arthur, among us.

When the reporter says, â€œA monster,â€ it breaks my heart. So many people need help but donâ€™t receive it and are seen as monsters. I truly hope the world becomes kinder in the future. Letâ€™s all try to be more compassionate. Wishing you all the best.

author: @leamorenalucero
text:
I love every Ounce of this Film. It has so many Layers that many cannot see it directly or need to catch up. The Music was added to make the Relationship between Arthur Fleck and Lee Quinzel romantic. She loved the Joker and not the real Person which is Arthur Fleck. This makes a lot of Sense too (a different Approach of the Relationship with Joker and Harley) that Lee later on finds the "other" Joker and sticks to an Idea of Him. The Plottwist in the End is fantastic. This Film is another great way to reflect on Humanity. What started out as an untreated Disease (or many false Information in the History) led to a false Inspiration / led to a Misinterpretation in the Present.

As mentioned, many Audience couldn't see it right away because there are so many Informations at once in this Film. The Music was wonderful sarcastic approach to over all how Humanity copes up or covers a lot through Music. Because sets the Mood of the Emotion and through that we tend to forget or neglect the Objective part of Life. "That is Entertainment" or better said Distraction!

Again, what a fantastic Move. Love it!

text: "I can't say I've ever been apart of the BMX crowd, but that certainly doesn't stop "Rad" from delivering the goods. What's really amusing about this movie is that it doesn't take long for its weaknesses to somehow become strengths, and that's all part of the charm. It's familiar (The Karate Kid, E.T.), it's bizarre (was that a school dance or a disco scene?) and I get a smile from seeing Canada as small-town America. But this is the kind of underdog story you can't help but like, and that's not even covering the movie's greatest weapon: the music. Farnham's "Thunder In Your Heart" is every bit the '80s time capsule that is "Rad".

text:
I didnt care much for the first one. It was far too much "taxi driver, Falling Down, and that one movie where De Niro kidnaps Jerry Lewis, walked into a bar..." but im actually stoked to see this one as soon as i can download it. It got my attention just how badly it pissed fans off, then i read everything QT had to say about it
The public's obsession with The Joker deserved to be shattered, and i am so glad HQ is going down with him. The line that QT said to get my attention was "it feels like it was made by the joker" idk im officially stoked. And again, its cool the first one broke box office records and all that nonsense, but my only feelings while watching it was "oh (they) did this in ____, (they) did that in ____" but idk despite this one being compared to NBK, has a great allure to it. At least theres no De Niro in it to tie it to not one but two previous de Niro flicks

Throughout the movie we found ourselves sighing at the tedious repetitive songs each time their mouths opened to sing. Personally, we never enjoyed it and was glad when it was over. However, if you like musicals, you might like it. Thumbs down from us though!

author: @EveryBeardHasAStory
text:
The Joker dies at the end of this.

For those of you that don't know, a lot of wealthy people took great offence to Heath Ledger's Joker. Specifically the money burning scene. That's why they killed Heath. Yes, really. This Joaquin Phoenix iteration was meant to subdue the Joker. To make him powerless. Like the billions of people who are powerless in the real world. The first movie was a half and half experience to ease audiences into this absolute train wreck of sheer, and outright hatred towards humanity. Do not watch this if you are a fan of the Joker character. Do not watch this if you feel you've been mistreated through life. Do not watch this if you are a DC fan. Do not watch this if you enjoyed the first movie. Plain and simple, do not watch this. This "movie" was nothing but a message from the wealthy to the poor that reads, and I quote: "You will never be free." I pirated this garbage and I am not only feeling buyers remorse, but absolute disgust. #DeathToTheRich

author: @bmwforlife6951
text: Spoiler alert I'm a huge fan of the first Joker (2019) movie. I've watched the Folie a Deux yesterday. Let me start with the positive aspects of this sequel. The whole atmosphere is the same as the first movie. Same lighting, same colors, same looks. The negative aspects: the accompanying music is the same as the first movie, most of the lines are the same as the first, Joker suddenly can sing (why?), it's very awkward to hear him singing. The storyline was very vague, when was it fantasy? When real? The ending when Joker dies was very unexpected. So the guy who killed him became the Joker? Interesting. That explains his cut mouth. 5.3 at IMDb is even too much. I would rate it a 3.

I think itâ€™s a very clever movie, the fact people are outraged will mean in years to come itâ€™ll be hailed as a film that captured the madness of our times.

author: @obsoletepowercorrupts
text:
I just watched the best two hour eighteen minute long cigarette advert. It's probably even better in the French version.
The sequel movie (Joker foie gras) was fine by me. It was more like Children Of Men (Clive Owen) mixed with Sweeney Todd (the Johnny Depp musical) than being like Natural Born Killers. It forces adults to stop taking kids toys by culturally appropriating action hero movies. Instead of snatching that candy from a baby, it lights an incendiary post-coital tobacco smoke. There's no getting smoked, without getting fired.
Now the World has been goosed, let's just hope that in the upcoming third instalment "Joker: MÃ©nage Ã  Foie" the implied baby-joker born from the fruitful loins of Harlequin is as good a gander.
In the law case which touched on the mentality, Joker could have kept mum about his predicted programming, and the third maybe just maybe could have him do that because an explosion at the court building is enough to force a retrial, especially since the jury had not finished saying what they had decided and also the car bomb could be argued legally as always having been an implicit event that might happen what with the publicity and crowds showing anger, which can sway and intimidate a jury.
Some people have said they are disappointed by the film, but it is probably because they do not see it as more like an art-film (hence the grey-pill Children-Of-Men gutsy ending and the Sweeney-Todd songs like a macabre Tim Burton) and instead they base it upon the first one. If you have not seen the Joker1 movie, the Joker2 movie has a chance at being considered something different to it. If there is a Joker3, we'll see.
My comment has no hate in it and I do no harm. I am not appalled or afraid, boasting or envying or complaining... Just saying. Psalms23: Giving thanks and praise to the Lord and peace and love. Also, I'd say Matthew6.

author: @melodylover0704
text:
I feel like some people think theyâ€™re cool for trashing this movie but havenâ€™t given a thought on what message itâ€™s trying to send.
This is probably exactly what the director imagined would happen; people in the movie idolizing â€œJokerâ€, being overly aggressive and critical because Arthur finally chose himself, are the same cynical people trashing this movie for it not being something they wanted it to be.

People (in the movie including Lee) only rooted for â€œJokerâ€, not Arthur, and didnâ€™t love him for who he actually is as a whole but put him on a pedestal as some kind of a hero and worshipped him like theyâ€™re in some kind of a cult. Once Arthur realized and confessed he couldnâ€™t keep up anymore, peopleâ€™s reactions changed 180Â°.
Many fans who watched the initial Joker expected the sequel to be something more dramatic and entertaining; so when they saw that Arthur was just Arthur, they acted just the same as the fans of Joker within the movie.

Everyone wants catharsis and hates to be shown the reality. Of course if Lee loved him as a whole it wouldâ€™ve been beautiful but in real life, not all love stories have a happy ending. And in the end, youâ€™re the only person who can accept yourself for who you are, unconditionally.

I think itâ€™s one thing to not like a movie but another thing to scoff and comment on it with so much disrespect.

author: @Scene-ByScene-7
text:
Joker: Folie Ã  Deux, a sequel that disappoints, Joaquin Phoenix and Lady Gaga offer a good performance giving life to two tormented and complex characters. However, it is the story that is full of holes.

While the first film had won us over with its psychological depth and its powerful social criticism, this second chapter seems to struggle to find its own identity. The plot, at times fragmented and predictable, cannot hold its own against its predecessor. The characters, although interesting, remain in the background compared to an action that gets lost in useless digressions.

In conclusion, Joker: Folie Ã  Deux is a film that leaves a bitter taste in the mouth, it is often even boring. Despite the technical merits and the excellent performances, the story is weak.

A sequel that disappoints expectations, with a poor plot and a much lower emotional impact than the first film.

author: @ChesterBarajan
text:
I BET TODD PHILLIPS KNEW EVEN BEFORE THE RELEASE THAT THERE WILL BE BACKLASH. (SPOILER BELOW)

When Lee said, "Let's give the people what they want.", it was in Arthur's fantasy. Because that really was Lee's mission in the film, - to empower the Joker in Arthur.; to fully convince Arthur that he is THE JOKER. Now, I get the gunshot in that particular scene. Arthur already had the fear that he may anger Lee if time comes, he'll decide not to give people what they want.

It was all intentional. Todd did not give the people what they wanted for Joker. Some angry, some disappointed, some just accepted it. Good for me, I came to the theater with no expectations. Though, I really don't mind the noise in social media right now about how bad this film is. Some even hated it just because it's a 'Musical', even though it's not really a musical film, considering the format. Well, who am I to judge? Art is subjective. What matters most is that - IT HAS BEEN SAID AND DONE. Whether you love or hate Joker 2, YOU GET WHAT YOU DESERVE.

author: @RobertoVargas-j7z
text:
Alright, I'm about to be publicly executed but I'm just gonna say it how it is.
This movie and the way everyone reacted to it was completely intentional and the universal hate it received proves its point.
This film is a deconstruction of the idealized image of The Joker fans have created from his portrayal in comic books and other media, including the first Joker movie as well.
This movie condemns those people who idolize and admire what can be objectively called a terrible, evil person. The Joker is an absolute monster. You shouldn't be looking up to him. You shouldn't want to see chaos and violence.
It's the same as with people unironicaly looking up to characters like Patrick Bateman. It's a delusional way of thinking and this movie serves as a very uncomfortable wake up call for them.
Fans feel as if this movie mocks and insults them. Well, yeah. Thats exactly it. The more you expected to see this villainous Joker you are familiar with, the more this movie was gonna hurt you.
After the first movie, people "sympathized" with Joker because, after being constantly put down by everyone else, he snaps and brings chaos and violence upon. People thought it was cathartic. Well, they missed the point.
Ever since the first movie, Arthur is depicted as a very mentally unhealthy individual who never got the help and attention he needed. The way he turns into the Joker isn't something to be happy about. It's extremely tragic. He is consumed by his own suffering and in a moment of despair he snaps. He unintentionally reaffirms the negative image society has about mentally unhealthy individuals. And although in the movie some mentally ill people find some kind of catharsis in this Joker persona, most of his followers are actually deranged criminals who just want an excuse to exercise violence without restraint.
It's the same with most of the audience. They viewed the conclusion of the first movie as something cool and exciting. As some kind of twisted power fantasy. Well, let me tell you, as someone who has struggled with mental illness and who has been neglected by family members and institutions his whole life, I found the end of the first movie extremely heartbreaking. Of course I want my struggle to be heard, but I don't want to turn into violence and depravity. Feeling represented in Arthur and turning into a Joker is the last thing most mentally unhealthy people want. Violence and destruction is not the answer. We just want help. Being part of the group of people actually discussed in this movie, I found the emotional, sad and depressing, portrayal of Arthur's character in the sequel way more compelling and relatable than any kind of "amazing" Joker violence fest.
In the sequel, Arthur himself becomes disgusted with his actions and with his Joker persona because he realizes just how much more damage he has caused. Arthur may have snapped and done awful things in the first movie, but he's not a psychopath who lacks empathy. On the contrary, hes extremely emotional and sentimental.
In the end, Arthur owns up to his actions and is abandoned and forgotten by everyone else who just looked at him due to his Joker persona. I've read about people deeming Arthur's inner struggle and insecurities as boring compared to the over-the-top Joker persona they wanted to see. Well, both Harley and everyone else in Gotham feel the exact same way. The fact the reaction of these characters is mirrored with the reaction of the audience itself is a brilliantly meta way for the message of the movie to be conveyed.
It's understandable why people felt disappointed because the last thing they wanted to see was a vulnerable, beaten down "Joker". They were expecting to see him turn into the Prince of Crime they love. But ever since the first movie, it wasnt a story about the villainous mastermind comic book Joker. It was a depressing story about a sad individual who accidentally creates a bigger than life public image and how he ends up being consumed by it.
I agree with this feeling of betrayal due to most of the marketing for the movie being very deceitful and how it essentially played with and made a "Joke" off of the fans. But I think it was a necessary evil.
Todd and Phoenix and GaGa were extremely bold to do something like this and it may have very well stained their careers and reputation, also having "wasted" 200+ mill dollars into what was essentially a very expensive social commentary. But at the end of the day, seeing how everyone thinks about this movie, it can be said that they actually succeeded at what they wanted to do.
They managed to provoke an overwhelming, universal emotional reaction (just as any work of art should do) into 99% percent of the audience. And it is truly spectacular.
You all feel like you were ridiculed by not getting what you wanted. You feel as if this movie condemned you for even daring to be a fan of the first movie. Well, I'm afraid to tell you that it is, indeed, your fault. It is your fault for expecting a conventional comic book movie. It is your fault for expecting a gratuitous spectacle of violence. It is your fault for wanting to see your beloved chaotic Joker. This movie is unapologetically raw and anger inducing. They wanted to go beyond the medium itself and into the real world perception of the movie. You were indeed played for a fool and, as I said before, it was completely intentional.
The fact something like this was even attempted at a bluckbuster, super hero movie flick level is insane. This kind of artistry is often found in this other very niche part of the film industry.
This is not even a "comic book film adaptation" at this point. It is an extremely meta, genre redefining, work of art which completely succeeded in doing what it intended to do. You just ended up being obliviously turned into the central piece of this social experiment. And it's truly amazing.
And to double down on it, the end of the film in which Arthur is killed by an actually deranged and psychotic criminal, allegedly being the "real" Joker, can be seen as the movie itself saying "Here you go. This is the Joker you wanted, right?".
What this "real" Joker says is actually directed at the audience itself.
"You got what you f###### deserved".

author: @sushi998
text: I liked it. I believe most people just can't see through the 'musical' vibe and want it to make sense. But to me those scenes feel deranged and out of place and that is exactly the point of it. In his head he is the entertainer/joker and she reawakens that imagination while he finds himself in reality is such a grim place. She wants him to escape for real, he just wants to escape through the idea of beeing loved. Like in the first movie he is quite estrangend from reality. Also I feel that the main message, how badly Arthur is struggling with his alter ego and his true self, is highlighted by the love story that (spoiler alert) turns out to be a scam because she only loves him for joker. It's not a classic super hero/villain story, it is not a musical, it is a deeply saddening story of a person abused as child, who escapes through imagination,  struggling to keep in touch with reality. With a few different choices this could have been another masterpiece, because to me the idea, the cinematography and the acting were actually very much on point. The movie seems to me very much misunderstood, just like Arthur, and maybe that makes it genius after all.

author: @made0041
text:
Am I the only one who actually liked the movie? Granted, I love musicals and the theatrical sort of Baz Luhrmann cinematic style, but I think the crazyness of them randomly breaking out into song and these different "dream sequences" with the Joker singing and dancing are a great representation of them living in their own fantasy world, and when he stops singing and asks her to as well, but she doesn't, was really meaningful, too. I don't know, I liked it.

Edit: Another thing, Joker's catch phrase, at least Heath Ledger's Joker, is literally "Why so serious". So, cutting the tension of the serious scenes with random singing and dancing, I think is the perfect picture of what Joker represents. But I do admit I wish they had been WAY more transparent with this basically being a musical, a completely different genre than the first one, that obviously won't appeal to the same exact audience, who had been looking forward to it. I still liked it, though.

author: @NikiWonoto26
text:
Most people who hate the ending actually just proves the point of this movie. It's because people have expectations for how it should end, which is mostly probably an epic ending, or a happy ending. But this movie subvert all expectations, because it shows a darker, sad, & bad ending. Movies like this are such a very rare exceptions, especially today, because it bravely defies all the 'escapism' fantasy like in most entertainment, fictions, & works of art. This movie actually portrays the harsh reality very much, in fact, it is very close to what happens to our everyday's real world. Maybe this is the much deeper reason why people subconsciously hate this movie: because it simply reminds them of the harsh, bleak, cold, cruel, & depressing reality. But for me, it's actually perfect, because again, it's extremely very rare to find a movie/film that is not just as a mere escapism & entertainment, but actually really portrays & shows the cruel reality.
- from Indonesia -

author: @sehu1291
text:
Give the film a chance. Just be prepared for a film in Arkham Asylum and in court with dream sequences. Don't expect an action film. The director knew what people would hate about the film. When they were dancing and singing in the show, the audience suddenly got quiet and Lee said to Joker: "The audience doesn't like what we're doing here, let's give them what they want and the music stopped and a violent scene was shown. Just like at the end he tells her to please stop singing, he covered her mouth but she just wouldn't stop. He asks because the director knew that the audience didn't want that either. The film plays with the audience's expectations.

Arthur is not THE Joker. He's not intelligent, he's not a criminal genius, he's just a mentally ill loser. Nothing more. He's an insignificant nobody. That was already clearly shown in part 1, but many viewers didn't get it and got it right in the face in this film who Arthur is. A loser. A nobody. You don't have to like a film, but anyone who talks about a disaster didn't understand Arthur Fleck and Part 1.

author: @Lord_HawHaw
text:
Just finished watching â€œJoker: Folie Ã  Deux.â€

The success of the first film is that it directly tapped into a socio-political undercurrent marked by societal frustration with issues pertaining to how we address mental and behavioral health, social welfare, and class disparity. It also appealed to those who have felt as though they have been the victim of social, political, health, and judicial systems that have allowed them to fall through the cracks and failed them.

To that end, people came to identify with Arthur Fleck. I remember watching it in the theater when the first one came out, and when he killed Murray- the crowd literally applauded and cheered the man that the film had just been building up to be the â€œBig Bad.â€ And because of that, the film was a massive success.

Obviously, the producers and writers (and we will just say the powers that be) felt that â€œJokerâ€ appealed to the - letâ€™s just say â€œwrong target audienceâ€- and that they needed an unnecessary sequel intentionally written to destroy every aspect of the first that audiences loved. Look it up- they intentionally wrote the second to erode the pillars that made the first such a success and Arthur Fleck a type of folklore hero.

â€œJoker: Folie Ã  Deuxâ€ is a humiliation ritual for an audience held captive who wanted a continuation of the first filmâ€™s success. And all of the legitimate appeal that the first had regarding the issues affecting the disenfranchised and harried masses was tossed aside, and the sentiments felt by the audience goers spit back in their faces.

And then Hollywood wonders why their initial projections for box office sales had to be negatively adjusted 60% lowerâ€¦.

Today, more than ever- We are all clowns.

text:
You know what? Todd Phillips is a genius.

At the end of Joker you're not going to tel me Arthur Fleck is going to be able to go toe to toe with Batman (unless Batman is also a loser in this universe after his parents died). There's no way this Joker is rigging up two boats with bombs and gives each other the detonators.

But this trailer had me thinking, okay, maybe Joker's insanity can make him basically a completely different person that's no longer the loser we saw for 90% of the movie whose first kill was out of self defense.

The Todd makes him the loser again in the sequel obviously to spite the fans of Joker. Well played, but who won?

author: @leorusso2480
text:
This movie was one of the most BRILLIANT ideas on cinema's history.

Itâ€™s not about the JOKER, itâ€™s about ARTHUR FLECK. The discomfort is intentional, showing how we idolize atrocities for the sake of spectacle, while wanting a real-life Arthur Fleck to rot in prison.

Itâ€™s a raw analysis of a mental condition and how it spreads quickly like a virus in our society addicted to dopamine hits from social media, fake news, pornography, and glorious martyrs who spark a wave of redpills across the world.

Itâ€™s an ANTI-HERO movie with a clear message: "F**K ALL OF YOU." Is there any trolling more Joker than that?

Joker 2: The Clown is YOU.
This is Cinema, Folks!

text:
I personally enjoyed the cinematography and the musical parts, even if some of them were lack luster. However, I wouldn't say I liked the direction of the film's plot, How I thought it would have gone is

start
joker in prison
joker meets Dr. Harley
they gain a romantic relationship
they lead each other further into each other's madness as the trial goes on
Harley breaks Joker out of whatever/prison/court
we end off with what regular joker would be

I believe that the musical was a good part though they should have advertised that more because it seemed some people didn't know but I'll continue on, it was a good way to show off the love he had for Harley feeding into the fantasy and escape that he feels with her.


Originally as I saw this being released I thought it was interesting. how I saw the 2019 Joker film was how people use comedy to mask and soothe the trauma and sadness from events in our lives, and how now in Folie a deux people use music to express love and passion

overall it could have been something better. ehrm...... womp womp this movie sucked

author: @emazur8394
text: The first Joker, though bleak, was fantastic. I was looking forward to Joker 2 but when I saw the trailer at the theater nothing made me want to see it. I saw it anyway and what you see is what you'll get. It's a very flat movie and little of interest happens. The unadvertised musical bits (which really don't take up that much airtime) sadly are probably the better parts of the movie. Harley Quinn the character was pretty flat in this one (it's not Lady Gaga's fault). Definitely not like the eccentric character from the Batman animated series. If you want a Harley Quinn movie, watch Birds of Prey (2020) instead. Joker 2 at best is a 2-star movie. If you intend to see it, if it hasn't caught your interest within the first 30 or 40 minutes it never will and I'd recommend bailing out.

author: @subhayuepaul
text:
The Joker sequel, if we approach it from a psychoanalytic and ideological perspective, reflects a deeper exploration of the failures of contemporary society, but it doesnâ€™t merely continue the narrative from the first film. Rather, it accentuates the original's critique of neoliberalism while exposing even more sharply the hidden underside of our political unconscious.

Arthur Fleck, in this sequel, no longer represents merely the victim of systemic violence; he becomes the embodiment of a certain enjoymentâ€”what Lacan calls jouissance. The chaos he instigates is not just social anarchy, but a direct manifestation of repressed desires bubbling up from beneath the surface of modern capitalist society. In this sense, the Joker isnâ€™t just a villain or antihero. Heâ€™s the symptom of a decaying ideologyâ€”an ideology that still maintains its appearance of order but is crumbling at its core.

This sequel deepens the tension between individual and system. Arthurâ€™s descent into madness, violence, and chaos becomes the logical outcome of a system that can no longer conceal its contradictions. Jokerâ€™s actions are not isolated acts of rebellion but the culmination of a societal failure where the individualâ€™s madness is a mirror of the larger collective madness.

Yet, the film does not offer a clear revolutionary path. In true Å½iÅ¾ekian fashion, it leaves us with the uncomfortable realization that our desires for change often lack form, that the systems we rail against are not easily destroyed, and that chaos without structure offers no alternative vision. Joker, in his madness, points to a deeper truth: the system itself is insane, and yet, perversely, it functions.

The filmâ€™s brilliance lies in how it forces us to confront this uncomfortable reality, how it reveals that perhaps the real joke is on usâ€”the audience, still searching for meaning, revolution, and redemption within a system that thrives on our discontent.

text: Given the brilliance of the original, if the creators had a strong story for a sequel, it should have truly lived up to 'Joker.' Instead, it feels like they rushed through a half-finished narrative, and the choice to make it a musical was a significant drawback. There were hardly any impactful moments that gave the audience chills. To top it off, the ending was quite disappointing. I really hope they consider making a third installment to redeem this experience!

author: @russell3436
text:
I watched it last night, it was boring as batshit, plot was a mess and all over the place, every musical part was just tacked on unnecessarily, not to mention the songs were vomit worthy and every time they happened the audience in my screening went on their phone and just let out a massive sigh of frustration as to why every scene needed some rubbish song tacked on.

The only redeeming part was the court case scenes and that was it, but even then that part was a 6.5/10 at best.

Why would you make a movie about the Joker who is meant to be this killer clown who enjoys anarchy and chaos into some goofy musical reminiscent of the 1930s-50s.

I was really dissapointed, Iâ€™ve never walked out of a movie before but I was so close to walking out, and the length was too long for its own good, being almost 2.5 hours was almost a death blow to your brain to fathom this atrocity.

author: @shobhitsharma3217
text:
Joker 2 was a travesty except cinematography, rewatched joker 1 12 hours prior to watching joker 2 and regretted it big time.

My plot that could have justified Joker 2 as true sequel . The first 5 minutes would have shown Joker's routine in the asylum, completely overshadowed by his Joker identity. The next 15 minutes would focus on court hearings, and then Harley would be introduced as Joker's psychiatrist. Over time, Joker's mindset would greatly influence Harley's identity, leading to her transformation from a normal mindset to a crazy one. Before the interval, a group of Joker's admirers breaks into the asylum and helps Joker escape. The second half of the plot would show Joker, Harley, and the group revolting against the system, leading to riots and punishing the wealthy with heinous acts.

Meanwhile, if they wish to recreate the scene from the first part where Bruce Wayne's story unfolds, they could depict the Joker walking into a palace and setting it on fire . The camera angle could show Bruce and Alfred witnessing the Joker's crazy act for the first time, setting the stage for their future rivalry. As for the ending, they could show the Joker and Harley isolating themselves from the city for a significant period after their destructive acts, or perhaps depict the Joker and Harley having a baby, setting the stage for Robert's Batman to face a similarly aged Joker (Arthur would not be alive). In a post-credit scene a few years later, they could show a new Joker wreaking havoc once again, with the camera angle revealing the shade of Robert watching it , leading into Batman 3.

text: This movie doesn't really have anything to do about the Joker other than using the concept of it and exploiting its fruits. It should have been named Arthur Fleck instead who is just a dumb, naive and predictable character in comparison with the first one along with having ZERO confidence as well when wearing the Joker suit and makeup for lame reasons. And there's literally the decline of characters instead of development. The song and dream sequences aren't profound at all and yet ridicilious, corny, awkward and boring. The movie clearly expects the audience to be stupid considering the explanation and justification of the acts of the first one, which only worked in the first one because of the mystique, imagination and myth of its dark tone while being in an exciting pace unlike this one. A dull and boring buildup made it lose its glamour early on and Arthur's realtionship with Lee/Harley has no significance at the end and was just a waste of time and story... Nice way to ruin an intriguing character of Joker overall...

text: BBC was part of the selected early screening reviewers. BBC reviews that a lot of things you see in the movie is just the imagination of Arthur and this sequel delievers the message that Fleck is a wimpy, self-centred stooge who lets down everyone around him. He's a nobody. Depending on how you look at it, this demythologising exercise is either daring or it's irritatingly smug, but it's definitely not much fun. Phillips seems to be saying that if you fell for Fleck's Messianic self-image the last time around, then the joke's on you.

author: @williamstellmon7565
text:
So as fan of Harley Quinn, it's kind of sad they took away her back story as the jokers psychologist at Arkham.
The had a PhD but was denied promotions and raises. She made a huge impact in reforming patients at Arkham.
The joker recognized that she was essentially their slave. Dealing with the patients no one else wanted to deal with.
Which is why she got the joker as a patient. Joker played the part of a reforming inmate.
Once Harley Quinn demostrated her methods we're effective. It was her supervisor that took credit for all of her work.
That is what broke Harley. That is when joker was able to open the door in her mind into becoming an agent of chaos.
I know the comics and animated series are not movie canon. It's just a shame to see such a complex character get reduced down.

author: @IconicPicturesInternational
text: Somebody at an executive level interfered and sabotaged this sequel. It is focused more on trying to attract a "new" audience than satisfying the audience it already has. As a result of the executive level narcissism and self serving ideology, the film mixes genres in a way that conflicts. The IP's core strength and concept has been gutted. It looks like an empty shell of it's former self. I LOVED the original, but cannot feel in my gut the desire to see this. As is so common these days with Hollywood films. They rarely appeal to my instincts and to the core of my being as the films once did. Instead they are trying to appeal to some cognitive, intellectual, social justice ideology that is keeping filmmakers stuck in their heads.

author: @TyDollar-f1
text:
Congratulations to Warner Bros for the decision to close down the servers of the Harry Potter: Magic Awakened game, many people have spent a lot of money on the game. It was active for about a year, who would have expected that a game with a little more than a year left would simply close its doors and we'd lose everything?

I saw in the chat that people stopped eating to put money into the game, others almost lost their wives or families from spending so much, all this for what? At the end of the day, Warner Bros puts the money in your pocket and goodbye?

This game helped not only me, but many people with depression, which is a very common disease these days, people who loved and loved the game who bet everything to see the game grow, people streaming on twitch and the game grew more and more, but it wasn't enough for Warner Bros.

I hope you manage to get out of this crisis you're going through, the stock market is getting worse and worse, I wish you every success but don't rob people, don't rob workers, people who put money into games for the first time and you just took it all.

author: @danclover5194
text: Joker is one of my all time favorite movies.was told it was a rip off of taxi driver and "king of comedy" never really bought into the taxi driver idea cuz its like Arthur is positive and hopeful in a way while Travis Bickle is just bitter right from the opening dialogue .. felt it a different tone entirely â€¦ after this trailer I watched "King of Comedy " and that movie is the first Joker but way better .. the scenes flow seamlessly from dream state to reality , you have no idea what is really going on and the ending was actually great that the comedy standup was funny by Robert Dinero  and the whole movie youre lead to believe hes not.. this new joker film looks like just a further continuation of Arthurs delusionsâ€¦ I honestly believe the "joke" the therapist wouldn't get at end of the first film , is the whole movie we watched was just some daydream of Arthur in Arkham asylum ,, he dreamed he got famous,  and everyone loved him that's "how he got there" .but in reality hes just a lunatic.  I feel like at the end of this second film it will be revealed that the entire two movies weren't realâ€¦ I believe this because after watching KofC you see that Robert Deniro Character is revered after going to jail and he comes back to a screaming audience yelling his name and they say it 8 times. throughout the movie , no one remembers his name , Hes invisible and forgettable, so its all just a big fantasy still going on in his head even from prison imo..reading about this movie Todd Phillips used KOFC as heavy influence for Joker, so the idea that none of the first movie happened and the second is even further into his delusions makes sense for a good finale.

author: @BlaknGold09
text: At what point do we see this criminal mastermind emerge?  He seems a far cry from that at this point.  Im a fan of Pheonix's portrayal of the Joker and the elements of the Joker that he captures masterfully...but when does the psycopathic criminal mastermind emerge and he actually becomes full blown Joker.  That we have yet to see and im hoping we finally do at some point in this movie but im getting a little restless here and im wondering how they are gonna take this Joker and do that.  Crazy he has...insane....i can give him that as well...but smart....not at all and how are they gonna make this guy here a criminal master mind?  That part is what im having trouble seeing develope.  This is where Heath Ledgers Joker set himself apart and im hoping that Pheonix's Joker can become that somehow although im having a hard time wrapping mty head around how THIS Joker is just gonna magically transform into someone who can outsmart or out think Bruce Wayne/Batman.  The intellect just isnt there and explaining how this Joker GETS that intellect is gonna be a real challenge.  Batman would completely obliterate him mentally and physically as it stands right now thus making it impossible for this Joker to ever be the arch nemesis of the Dark Knight.

author: @benmacsanders7292
text: I was skeptical when I first found out that this film would have a certain focus on musical numbers, but after watching the first trailer and this second one, I think itâ€™s going to be really interesting. Prioritizing the focus and narrative around the Joker, taking a deep dive into his philosophy and identity in his own world separate from Batman and anything related to DC Comics, is such a refreshing and engaging experience for me personally. The character has been connected to pretty much a blank canvas when it comes to background, storytelling, and development. For me, Iâ€™m thankful that the first movie was written well enough to bring more life and existence to the Joker. By the looks of things, this new film is shaping up to be a positive addition to the character of the Joker.

author: @maverickcreations8864
text:
This is not the joker at all. This is just a sad, pathetic, incompetent-at-his-job incel in a costume. With a dumb blonde MTG for a consort.

The joker is ridiculously smart ! In fact the reason his stand-ups didn't work when he was normal was because it was way ahead and so cutting it went above his audience's heads. He knew all the flaws of the system but he was ok trying to make a life with his wife.

After his accident and the death of his wife, his smartness went from making jokes on the system to making a joke of the system.

There's a reason why they Batman is always nervous about his schemes. Joker knows the game as well as he does if not better.

There's a reason the Joker was able to make a psychiatrist like Harley Quinn fall for him. He was sharp as a diamond pretending to be a clown.

The joker which Joaquin Phoenix plays is just like any fool who feels the system is against him and goes on a rage spree. In the world 10 years ago, he would be put down.

The movie is more a commentary on MAGA America, it's supporters of nitwits, and the nonsense they are willing to believe and support than anything to do with the Joker.

author: @theoldkobold
text: Folie Ã  deux is a rare psychiatric syndrome that causes two or more people in a close relationship to share a delusion. The term is French for "double madness" or "madness for two". The primary patient, who has a psychotic disorder, influences the other person or people (secondary patients) to share their delusions. The delusions can be identical or similar, and can be shared in part or in whole.

author: @cherylrleigh1912
text:
Folie Ã  deux (French for 'madness of two'), also known as shared psychosis or shared delusional disorder (SDD), is a psychiatric syndrome in which symptoms of a delusional belief are "transmitted" from one individual to another.

The disorder, first conceptualized in 19th century French psychiatry by Charles LasÃ¨gue and Jules Falret, is also known as LasÃ¨gueâ€“Falret syndrome. Recent psychiatric classifications refer to the syndrome as shared psychotic disorder (DSM-4 â€“ 297.3) and induced delusional disorder (ICD-10 â€“ F24), although the research literature largely uses the original name. The same syndrome shared by more than two people may be called folie Ã  trois ('three') or quatre ('four'); and further, folie en famille ('family madness') or even folie Ã  plusieurs ('madness of several').

This disorder is not in the current, fifth edition of the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders (DSM-5), which considers the criteria to be insufficient or inadequate. DSM-5 does not consider Shared Psychotic Disorder (folie Ã  deux) as a separate entity; rather, the physician should classify it as "Delusional Disorder" or in the "Other Specified Schizophrenia Spectrum and Other Psychotic Disorder" category.

author: @domenicoloriggio7315
text:
Non finirÃ² mai di ringraziare il mio migliore amico Nicola. All' epoca del primo Joker ero un po' chiuso nel mio angolino visto che film come V per Vendetta, 300, Sin City, Watchmen, i Batman di Burton e Nolan, Scott Pilgrim vs The World, la saga videoludica Batman Arkham, i due Injustice, Hulk di Ang Lee e relativo videogioco per PS2, Superhero, i film live action delle Tartarughe Ninja, La Leggenda degli Uomini Straordinari, Il Corvo, i due Gli Incredibili, Megamind, Smallville, Krypton, i film live action di Garfield e i due Hellboy di Del Toro erano ormai passati. E principalmente portavo in palmo di mano Marvel's Spider-Man, Into the Spider-verse, il DC animated universe, Invincible e The Boys (l' Arrowverse aveva i suoi alti e bassi. PerÃ² almeno c'era Superman & Lois). Un giorno il mio migliore amico Nicola mi disse che al cinema davano un film chiamato 'Joker'. Io ero scettico. "Dai, Nico', un film su Joker senza Batman non potrebbe mai funzionare. Sarebbe come fare un film su Lex Luthor senza Superman". All' uscita dal cinema Nicola mi disse che quel film ricordava molto 'Taxi Driver' e 'Re per una notte' (film che non ho mai visto, ndr). Nonostante non fosse una trasposizione del fumetto 'The Killing Joke' (ancora grazie, Nello, per avermelo regalato) il primo Joker mi era piaciuto tantissimo. Nicola si ricorda ancora oggi che gli feci la testa ad acqua con Joker, Toy Story 4 e Rocketman.

Alla notizia che avrebbero fatto Joker 2 rimasi F4 basito. Cosa avrebbero mai potuto raccontare visto che il Joker di Phoenix e il Batman di Pattinson non erano collegati? Il primo trailer ha fugato qualche dubbio. "Wow, allora mostrano decentemente, non come ha fatto il Suicide Squad di Ayer, come la dott.ssa Quinzeel Ã¨ diventata Harley Quinn. E magari finalmente mostrano il rapporto tossico tra Joker e Harley Quinn".

Questo secondo trailer sembra aver confermato, perÃ² mi toccherÃ  scoprirlo ad ottobre in sala, uno dei pronostici che avevo fatto per Joker 2: ci sarÃ  un duello nell' aula di tribunale tra Joker e Harley Quinn (che saranno visti come dei paladini) contro Harvey Dent che sarÃ  una specie di Jack McCoy che magari mira a diventare sindaco di Gotham City (chi ha visto Law & Order capirÃ ).

Per il resto che dire... Ad inizio anno avevo detto che c'erano solo tre film che aspettavo tantissimo, contando i secondi, allo stesso livello con cui ho aspettato ogni stagione di Attack On Titan e il Gear 5 nell' anime di One Piece. E ora aspetto Death Stranding 2, GTA VI, Kingdom Hearts 4, Resident Evil 9 gioco, The Last of Us s2, House of the Dragon s3, The Boys s5, Michael e Verum Rex gioco. Quei film erano Joker 2, Il Gladiatore 2 e Sonic 3. Appuntamento tra 2 mesi e 12 giorni con Joker 2. Poi passerÃ² al Gladiatore 2 e Sonic 3. Ma quella Ã¨ un' altra storia.

N.B. A molti miei conoscenti non piace il fatto che Joker 2 avrÃ  elementi musicali. A me sta benissimo. Infatti ho visto addirittura dieci volte film come Barbie, Super Mario Bros il film, Aladdin cartone, Hercules cartone Disney, Elvis del 2022, i due Sing, La Bella e La Bestia cartone, La Sirenetta cartone, La Principessa e il Ranocchio, Il Gobbo di Notre Dame, il primo Rio, Rocketman, La La Land, Another Cinderella Story, A Cinderella Story Once Upon a Song, i tre Pitch Perfect e Bohemian Rhapsody. Ed Ã¨ una cosa che ho riservato solo al primo American Pie, Shrek 2 e Superhero con Drake Bell. Comunque nessuno batterÃ  mai la Fata Madrina che canta 'I Need a Hero' in Shrek 2.

P.s. Non faccio previsioni in ottica Oscar. Soprattutto dopo che ho completamente cannato il risultato della finale degli europei di calcio Spagna-Inghilterra.

text:
To me, this is like the sequel to a really, really, REALLY good horror movie. Just listen to the first film's soundtrack and tell me it's not a horror flick about a clown that kills people.
Even now, in this trailer, i hear an disharmonious sound, in the background i hear something threatening, sinister and in the front, almost trying to deafen the eerie tune, thus properly embodying what the film is about :
It's about a mad dangerous man being treated like a hero when he's really just a monster who will be stopped again and again by another mad man, except this one wears a silly bat costume and overall has a weird thing with bats. But since this is a movie about the joker, i reckon batman won't be showing up a lot wich is kind of ironic.

author: @VLFBERHTwolf
text:
You know, it's funny. This trailer reminds me of a joke. See, there were two guys locked in a lunatic asylum and one night ... one night, they decided they didn't like that anymore. They decided to escape. So, they made it up to the roof and there, just across this narrow gap, they see rooftops, stretching across town, stretching to freedom. Now, the first guy, he jumps right across, no problem. But his friend, oh, no way, he's afraid of falling. So, the first guy has an idea. He says, "Hey, I got this flashlight with me. I'll shine it across the gap between the buildings and you can walk across the beam and join me." But the second guy says, "What do you think I am, crazy? You'll just turn it off when I'm halfway across!"

I wonder what parts of this movie are real and what parts are a hallucination.

author: @monster_fiz_the_story_lover
text:
I just gonna leave this note here for the nerd or those whose curious.

"Folie Ã€ Deux" is French for "madness shared by two." In psychology, Itâ€™s a rare psychiatric syndrome where delusional beliefs and hallucinations are transmitted from one individual to another. Imagine two people so close they start sharing the same crazy ideas. Itâ€™s like a twisted version of a shared Netflix account, but for delusions instead of TV shows.

Usually, one person is the primary, the originator of the delusion, and the other, the secondary, adopts these beliefs. Itâ€™s a fascinating and somewhat disturbing peek into how closely intertwined our minds can become with those weâ€™re emotionally connected to. So, next time you think your roommate is making you crazy, you might be more right than you know.

In criminal cases, it typically appears in situations where two people commit crimes together and share delusional beliefs, often reinforcing each otherâ€™s paranoia or grandiosity. Think of infamous duos like Bonnie and Clyde or the Moors murderers, though not always diagnosed with Folie Ã  Deux, their close relationships and shared delusions led to their criminal actions. And in this case, same thing happened with Arthur and soon to be his Harley queen in this trailer.

And depending on the situation and condition, it can transform into Folie Ã  Plusieurs, or "madness of many." This phenomenon occurs when one individualâ€™s delusional beliefs spread to multiple people, often in a group setting. So, with that in mind, perhaps we might have chance for the third movie if joker madness and delusional ideology keep spreading in the movie like what we see in the trailer, but hey, that just a theory, a film theory.

author: @ghostsurfer23
text: I'm sure the movie is going to be great, but I really wish the version of Harley that existed in this world was a psychologist like her origin. So little modern media utilizes that part of her character and it's by far the most interesting part. It would have been so interesting, with the way Arthur's relationship with psychologists and other doctors was in the first movie, to see someone who genuinely wants to help him but also loves him for him, who comes to worship him like he's always wanted to be worshipped. Most modern Harleys are reduced to "hot and crazy," and while I'm certain Gaga's version will have layers, it seems like it's gonna be just more "hot and crazy." That's a little disappointing.

author: @ProfDanielVargas
text:
I don't know what it is but something isn't clicking with me, with previous trailer and this trailer.

Either there's something wrong, that certainly doesn't feel right; we're missing something big or important that is not being shown here which contributes to making it feel not right; There's something hidden or misleading, intentionally cut from the trailers; or - I don't want to be neither pessimistic nor misogynistic - maybe it's Lady Gaga's acting and she doesn't feel right in the role and makes it feel off somehow.

Hopefully once the movie is released we get to see the whole picture and judge free of any biases or prejudice and form our fair opinion wether they did a good job or not.

Also, is that Brendan Gleeson? Why did I think that he had passed away?

text: Love the acting, mood, visuals and everything but I absolutely hate the retarded version of the Joker. So much so that it is impossible to predict his actions making him so hard to catch and only the absolute freaks are around him. But this version of Joker is just retarded and is strangely supported by the public - which is not something that would happen to Joker in DC comics since his insanity is beyond regular people's understanding. Moreover, I cannot imagine him tricking anyone with his low level of intelligence.

author: @LordFunzo
text:
Ehh, the first Joker got away with being basically a retarded clown because the movie was fresh, I am not sure that will wash this time.

Joker is supposed to be a criminal mastermind able to stay ahead of Batman. This portrayal is like he's the evil, anti-establishment messiah. You would just put him in solitary or have him executed - I am guessing they try both of these in the film and each time, the people save him, very anti-christ, he died for our sins but the Joker lives to make a mockery of virtue.

Mmm, there is probably a good film there, I just want to see his genius rather than fated happenstance but I can't because this incarnation of him is an idiot.

author: @rickfury1
text: "Folie Ã  Deux" is a French term that translates to "madness of two." It refers to a psychiatric syndrome where delusional beliefs or hallucinations are transmitted from one individual to another. This condition usually involves two people who are closely related or have a close emotional connection, such as family members or romantic partners. The shared psychotic disorder can sometimes extend to more than two people, in which case it is referred to as folie Ã  plusieurs ("madness of many").
